{#
  ClusterRoleBinding granting OpenBao's ServiceAccount permission to call
  the kube-apiserver's TokenReview endpoint. Required by the OpenBao
  Kubernetes auth method: when ESO (or any other client) presents a
  Kubernetes ServiceAccount token to OpenBao at
  POST /v1/auth/kubernetes/login, OpenBao calls
  POST /apis/authentication.k8s.io/v1/tokenreviews on the kube-apiserver
  to verify the token. The kube-apiserver authorizes that call by checking
  whether OpenBao's own SA holds the 'system:auth-delegator' ClusterRole.

  The 'system:auth-delegator' role is built into Kubernetes and grants
  exactly two permissions:
    - create tokenreviews.authentication.k8s.io
    - create subjectaccessreviews.authorization.k8s.io
  Nothing else. Binding it here is the minimum permission OpenBao needs to
  validate incoming SA tokens; it does not let OpenBao read any cluster
  state, mutate any resources, or read any secrets.

  Variables:
    openbao_namespace:    Namespace where the OpenBao StatefulSet runs and
                          where its ServiceAccount lives.
    openbao_sa_name:      Name of OpenBao's ServiceAccount (created by the
                          openbao Helm chart with serviceAccount.create:
                          true; defaults to the release name 'openbao').
#}
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: '{{ openbao_sa_name }}-auth-delegator'
subjects:
  - kind: ServiceAccount
    name: '{{ openbao_sa_name }}'
    namespace: '{{ openbao_namespace }}'
roleRef:
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: 'system:auth-delegator'
